  "Policy A is more sustainable because subsidies encourage maximum food production": "",
  "Policy B better serves long-term food security by building soil health, reducing water pollution, and creating resilience. Fertilizer subsidies (Policy A) encourage overuse, degrading soil and water quality over time, ultimately undermining the production base.": "",
  "A region with increasing population pressure is debating whether to expand agriculture into remaining natural grasslands or intensify production on existing farmland. An ecologist argues that converting the grasslands would destroy carbon stored in prairie soils and eliminate habitat for pollinators that also serve nearby farms. How does this scenario illustrate the tension between food production and ecosystem services?": "",
  "Intensifying production on existing farmland would have identical environmental impacts to expansion according to conventional analysis": "",
  "Converting grasslands provides short-term food production gains but destroys carbon stocks and pollinator habitat that support long-term agricultural productivity, illustrating why ecosystem services must be valued in agricultural decisions": "",
  "Ecosystem services are irrelevant to agricultural productivity, particularly regarding into under the given assumptions": "",
  "There is no tension because more farmland always means more food production as predicted by standard models": "",
  "This illustrates a key tension: expanding agriculture into natural ecosystems provides short-term food gains but destroys valuable ecosystem services (carbon storage, pollination) that support long-term agricultural productivity, showing why sustainable intensification on existing land is often preferable.": ""
